					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-13587505#post-4731369</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-13587505/scp-5639#post-4731369</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Mon, 27 Jul 2020 19:08:01 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>DalaiLlama</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1750870</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <blockquote> <p>This interview took place in the apparent chapel of SCP-5639. Although SCP-5639-1 had largely avoided Miranda.aic, it confronted her upon entry to the chapel. SCP-5639-1 spoke in Italian, Latin, and a portmanteau of the two that left some ambiguity in interpretation.</p> </blockquote> <p>I'm sorry, but this part (and the interview afterwards) took me out of the story. As a Romance language, Italian descends from Latin, meaning that it inherited most of the vocabulary of Latin as it developed.</p> <p>This means that lines like:</p> <blockquote> <p>SCP-5639-1: You do not [belong/live] here. This is a [cursed/holy] [prison/chapel].</p> </blockquote> <p>or</p> <blockquote> <p>SCP-5639-1: You must [leave/stay]. [I'm/He's] going to [kill/save] you.</p> </blockquote> <p>are inaccurate, since the amount of loanwords between the two languages means that there's little ambiguity in the translation (at least, not as much ambiguity as the interviews lead you to believe), especially for a mixed language that draws on both Italian and Latin.</p> <p>Prison in Latin, for instance, is <em>carcerum</em>, with a clear descendant in the form of the Italian <em>carcere</em>.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-13587505#post-4730435</guid>
				<title>Site Crit Team</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-13587505/scp-5639#post-4730435</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sun, 26 Jul 2020 22:16:25 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>ManyMeats</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>2104082</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Saying &quot;standard monastic layout&quot; bothers me a lot more than it should; these buildings were not constructed from blueprints and universal templates.</p> <p>You say that the AIC does the interview but you don't introduce how at all. At the end of the interview you mention a drone but there's no setup at all. We got from description right into &quot;AIC is interviewing&quot;. It was a grating transition</p> <p>I also found the <em>very frequent</em> split/text from the first interview to be very distracting.</p> <p>Overall the pace of this article was a good deal too slow for the payoff. The liturgical blocks bogged this down big time for me. I was a -1.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
